WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.200
A periodic boundary wave becomes smaller and later as it travels through an aquifer.

2
00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:10.700
Classical amplitude and phase inversions can yield two different diffusivities from that same wave.

3
00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:15.600
Lagging Theory represents causal field-scale memory, not a rigid time shift.

4
00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:20.200
Present Darcy flux is assembled from a weighted history of hydraulic gradients.

5
00:00:20.200 --> 00:00:26.000
Two response times distinguish flux adjustment from head equilibration.

6
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Mass conservation combines with the memory law to yield a lagging groundwater-flow equation.

7
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.100
Under harmonic forcing, attenuation and phase arise from the real and imaginary wavenumber components.

8
00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:43.800
Their ratio maps when amplitude- and phase-derived diffusivities disagree.

9
00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:50.100
Field transfer functions provide observed amplitude ratios and phase shifts at each frequency.

10
00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:55.300
One parameter set fits both signatures at Tuolumne Meadows and the Meghna River.

11
00:00:55.300 --> 00:01:00.400
AIC tests whether the improved fit justifies the two added lag parameters.

12
00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:05.700
Measurement error generates five thousand plausible amplitude-phase data sets.

13
00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:10.900
Each realization is refitted within bounded parameter space.

14
00:01:10.900 --> 00:01:15.700
Interquartile filtering removes aberrant refits before uncertainty is summarized.

15
00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:20.600
Posterior means and one-standard-deviation widths describe the retained parameter ensemble.

16
00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:26.000
A finite-difference solution independently checks the analytical amplitude and phase response.

17
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.200
Morris sensitivity shows how information changes with frequency, lag ratio, and observation distance.

18
00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:37.100
The same causal law resolves two different field-scale lag regimes without claiming a unique microscopic mechanism.
